node.text: Video by Keith Ladzinski @ladzinski / These are the structural remains of an old monastery high above the valley floor along the Tibetan Plateau. I filmed this little clip here on the way to Mount Everest Base Camp. The road passes through valley after valley full of rich history and old ruins such as these.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 13, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, dog and outdoors.

node.text:
Photo by @estherhorvath / Trude Hohle, a citizen of Longyearbyen, Svalbard, holds a puppy at a private dog yard outside the city. Because of wildlife protection, there are many rules in Svalbard. Dogs are not allowed to run free. They must stay in a dog yard outside of town and be on their leash when walking. Many locals have their own dogs that they use for dog sledding, and the dogs are wonderful company during the dark months of the polar night. Trude left her business life in Oslo behind and moved to Longyearbyen, following her dreams to work and live in one of the northernmost Arctic places on Earth. She spends much of her free time training and handling polar dogs.
Please follow @estherhorvath for more polar stories.

node.text: Photo by @kahliaprilphoto / Stars drift across the sky on a perfectly calm night in Banff National Park. The lake turned into a giant mirror, reflecting the stars and the Milky Way. It felt like you could stand on the sky!

node.text: Photo by @dina_litovsky / I love walking around New York City at night and catching fleeting moments happening inside the metropolis. This image was taken in the East Village. For more photos, follow me @dina_litovsky.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 12, 2021. May be an image of tree and nature.

node.text:
Photo by @stephen_matera / Larch trees in autumn color the Alpine Lakes Wilderness in the central Cascades, Washington. The larch is a deciduous conifer that grows in the mountains of the western United States and Canada. Its surprisingly soft needles turn golden yellow and fall off in autumn. I love these trees because they glow when backlit by the sun. 
Follow me @stephen_matera for more images like this from Washington and around the world. #larch #DeciduousConifer #autumn

node.text: Photo by @daisygilardini / There's nothing better than finding an Adélie penguin perfectly framed on an iceberg in Antarctica! When shooting environmental portraits, the main focus is to create a storytelling image that shows the subject in its habitat. Follow me @daisygilardini for more images and behind-the-scenes stories. #antarctica #penguin #adeliepenguin #iceberg #climatechange

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 12, 2021. May be an image of cloud and nature.

node.text:
Photo by @amivitale / Storm clouds gather over the peaks of the Matthews Range in northern Kenya, home to Reteti Elephant Sanctuary (@r.e.s.c.u.e), the first ever community-owned and community-run elephant sanctuary in Africa. In the 1990s elephant populations here had been poached to near extinction. Thanks to community-based conservation, elephants have made an extraordinary comeback. Today, there are more than 8,700 elephants in the area, making it Kenya's second largest population of elephants. Nature is resilient, when we give it a chance.
Follow @amivitale and @r.e.s.c.u.e to learn more, including how you can help. @kenyawildlifeservice @thephotosociety #protectelephants #elephants #stoppoaching #kenya #empathyiseverything

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 10, 2021. May be an image of nature, twilight, sky and mountain.

node.text: Photo by @sofia_jaramillo5 / Dusk falls outside Surveyors Lookout near Avery, Idaho. Fire lookouts used to play a vital role in maintaining safety and industry in the heavily wooded Pacific Northwest. At their peak, there were more than 8,000 maintained fire lookouts across the United States. Decommissioned lookouts are sometimes available to reserve through the National Forest Service for a unique camping experience above the treetops. #pnw #firelookout #hiking

node.text: Photo by @sarah_stacke / A car leaves a trail of dust on the Cheyenne River Reservation, a sovereign Lakota nation in South Dakota. Covering roughly 4,200 square miles (10,900 square kilometers), it is the fourth largest reservation in the country. Click the link in our bio for more on this story. Follow @sarah_stacke for more photographs and stories looking at the history of the Cheyenne River Lakota Nation and the United States. #CheyenneRiverLakota #SouthDakota #CountryRoads #Lakota #GreatPlains
